<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="69" type="taxonomy">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Taxonomy.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="69">
The specimens in the RAB were identified by comparison to a paratype 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Verbenaceae" genus="C." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="C. brevis" order="Tubiflorae" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="brevis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">C. brevis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which is also in the RAB. Browne put this species in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="platypodidae" genus="Platypus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Platypus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Platypus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Herbst, noting that the apical emargination of the elytra was rather similar to that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chapuis" authorityYear="1865" class="Insecta" family="platypodidae" genus="Platypus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Platypus caliculus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caliculus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Platypus caliculus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<bibRefCitation author="Chapuis, F" journalOrPublisher="Dessain, Liege" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" refId="B14" refString="Chapuis, F, 1865. Monographie des Platypides. H. Dessain, Liege" title="Monographie des Platypides. H." year="1865">Chapuis 1865</bibRefCitation>
(
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/00305316.1975.10434499" author="Beaver, RA" journalOrPublisher="Oriental Insects" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" pagination="283 - 211" refId="B5" refString="Beaver, RA, Browne, FG, 1975. The Scolytidae and Platypodidae (Coleoptera) of Thailand: a checklist with biological and zoogeographical notes. Oriental Insects 9 (3): 283 - 211, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/00305316.1975.10434499" title="The Scolytidae and Platypodidae (Coleoptera) of Thailand: a checklist with biological and zoogeographical notes." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/00305316.1975.10434499" volume="9" year="1975">Beaver and Browne 1975</bibRefCitation>
). In fact, 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Verbenaceae" genus="C." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="C. brevis" order="Tubiflorae" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="brevis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">C. brevis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has the typical characters of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Crossotarsus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Crossotarsus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Crossotarsus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: labial palps two-segmented, with basal segments fused in the midline, whereas 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="platypodidae" genus="Platypus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Platypus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Platypus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has the labial palps three-segmented, with separate basal segments. 
<bibRefCitation author="Beaver, RA" journalOrPublisher="Serie B fuer Botanik und Zoologie" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" pagination="179 - 192" refId="B1" refString="Beaver, RA, 1998. New synonymy, new combinations and taxonomic notes on Scolytidae and Platypodidae (Insecta: Coleoptera). Annalen des Naturhistorischen Museums in Wien. Serie B fuer Botanik und Zoologie 100: 179 - 192" title="New synonymy, new combinations and taxonomic notes on Scolytidae and Platypodidae (Insecta: Coleoptera). Annalen des Naturhistorischen Museums in Wien." volume="100" year="1998">Beaver (1998)</bibRefCitation>
transferred the species from 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="platypodidae" genus="Platypus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Platypus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Platypus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wood" authorityYear="1993" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Dinoplatypus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Dinoplatypus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Dinoplatypus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Wood following 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.part.16605" author="Wood, SL" journalOrPublisher="Great Basin Naturalist" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" pagination="259 - 281" refId="B37" refString="Wood, SL, 1993. Revision of the genera of Platypodidae (Coleoptera). Great Basin Naturalist 53 (3): 259 - 281, DOI: https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.part.16605" title="Revision of the genera of Platypodidae (Coleoptera)." url="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.part.16605" volume="53" year="1993">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Wood’s">Wood's</normalizedToken>
(1993)
</bibRefCitation>
attempt to split the genus 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="platypodidae" genus="Platypus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Platypus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Platypus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Wood diagnosed 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wood" authorityYear="1993" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Dinoplatypus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Dinoplatypus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Dinoplatypus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
largely on the basis of the circular, truncate, elytral declivity of the male, with the sutural apex emarginate. However, this is an adaptive character of the declivity which has evolved independently more than once in the 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Platypodinae">Platypodinae</taxonomicName>
, as it has in the 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Scolytinae">Scolytinae</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/B978-0-12-417156-5.00002-2" author="Hulcr, J" editor="Vega, FE" journalOrPublisher="Biology and Ecology of Native and Invasive Species. Academic Press, London" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" pagination="41 - 84" refId="B18" refString="Hulcr, J, Atkinson, TH, Cognato, AI, Jordal, BH, Mckenna, DD, 2015. Morphology, taxonomy, and phylogenetics of bark beetles. In: Vega, FE, Hofstetter, RW, Eds., Bark Beetles. Biology and Ecology of Native and Invasive Species. Academic Press, London: 41 - 84, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/B978-0-12-417156-5.00002-2" title="Morphology, taxonomy, and phylogenetics of bark beetles." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/B978-0-12-417156-5.00002-2" volumeTitle="Bark Beetles." year="2015">Hulcr et al. 2015</bibRefCitation>
). Molecular phylogenetic study also shows that the few morphological characters used by 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.part.16605" author="Wood, SL" journalOrPublisher="Great Basin Naturalist" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" pagination="259 - 281" refId="B37" refString="Wood, SL, 1993. Revision of the genera of Platypodidae (Coleoptera). Great Basin Naturalist 53 (3): 259 - 281, DOI: https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.part.16605" title="Revision of the genera of Platypodidae (Coleoptera)." url="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.part.16605" volume="53" year="1993">Wood (1993)</bibRefCitation>
to erect several groups of Neotropical and Indo-Malayan/Australasian species in 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" rank="tribe" tribe="Platypodini">Platypodini</taxonomicName>
to new genera are not sufficiently diagnosable for all those groups (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ympev.2015.05.028" author="Jordal, BH" journalOrPublisher="Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" pagination="294 - 307" refId="B20" refString="Jordal, BH, 2015. Molecular phylogeny and biogeography of the weevil subfamily Platypodinae reveals evolutionarily conserved range patterns. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution 92: 294 - 307, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ympev.2015.05.028" title="Molecular phylogeny and biogeography of the weevil subfamily Platypodinae reveals evolutionarily conserved range patterns." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ympev.2015.05.028" volume="92" year="2015">Jordal 2015</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="69">
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/00222936108651189" author="Browne, FG" journalOrPublisher="Insecta Mundi" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" refId="B13" refString="Browne, FG, 1961. Taxonomic notes on Platypodidae (Coleoptera). Annals and Magazine of Natural History, Series 13, 4(47): 641-656. https://doi.org/10.1080/00222936108651189" title="Taxonomic notes on Platypodidae (Coleoptera). Annals and Magazine of Natural History, Series 13, 4 (47): 641 - 656." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/00222936108651189" year="1961">Browne (1961)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.3931.3.4" author="Beaver, RA" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" pagination="401 - 412" refId="B7" refString="Beaver, RA, Sanguansub, S, 2015. A review of the genus Carchesiopygus Schedl (Coleoptera: Curculionidae: Platypodinae), with keys to species. Zootaxa 3931 (1): 401 - 412, DOI: https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.3931.3.4" title="A review of the genus Carchesiopygus Schedl (Coleoptera: Curculionidae: Platypodinae), with keys to species." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.3931.3.4" volume="3931" year="2015">Beaver and Sanguansub (2015)</bibRefCitation>
suggested that the adult generic characters of primary value in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Crossotarsus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Crossotarsus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Crossotarsus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
included the structure of the labial and maxillary palps, the form of the pronotum, the sexual dimorphism of the protibia, and various modifications of the abdominal sternites in the male. Based on the two-segmented labial palps, the lateral pronotal emarginations angulate anteriorly, the pronotum without mycangial pores, and the sexual dimorphism of the protibiae, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lai &amp; Zhang &amp; Li &amp; Wang" authorityYear="2021" baseAuthorityName="Lai &amp; Zhang &amp; Li &amp; Wang" baseAuthorityYear="2021" class="Insecta" family="platypodidae" genus="Platypus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Platypus brevis" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Platypus brevis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
belongs in the genus 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Crossotarsus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Crossotarsus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Crossotarsus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and is here transferred to that genus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="69" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Distribution.</paragraph>
